<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="151" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,760,764,2067]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,764,787]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
In habitus, most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1984" box="[554,656,764,787]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sargon">
<emphasis box="[554,656,764,787]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. sargon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, differing mainly in slightly smaller size and wider body, in narrower scutellum, and, probably, in its less shiny and less dark body [
<emphasis box="[224,246,860,883]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">vs</emphasis>
. “very shiny” in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1984" box="[445,552,860,883]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sargon">
<emphasis box="[445,552,860,883]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. sargon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; body of this new species slightly shinier and slightly darker than usual in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,259,924,947]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis box="[151,259,924,947]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and less shiny than usual in 
<taxonomicName authority="Gapon, 2021" authorityName="Gapon" authorityYear="2021" box="[575,722,924,947]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="essedonius" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[575,722,924,947]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. essedonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="18" pageNumber="151" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
], less convex disk of pronotun and calli, larger eyes, more widely rounded preocular part of head. Pale stripe of lateral margins of hemelytra posteriorly extremely narrow, disappearing (
<figureCitation box="[303,387,1052,1075]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[151,182,1834,1853]" captionTargetBox="[164,1391,218,1805]" captionTargetId="figure-13@4.[151,1436,189,1820]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Exosehirus species, general appearance from dorsal side and type labels. A – E. validus (Jakovlev, 1877), holotype; B – E. elamensis sp. nov., holotype; C – E. essedonius sp. nov., holotype; D – E. marginatus (Signoret, 1881), without abdomen, from Turkey." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037288/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Preocular part of head usually as in 
<taxonomicName box="[178,285,1084,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis box="[178,285,1084,1107]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but slightly less narrowly rounded anteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[189,276,1116,1139]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[150,181,2008,2027]" captionTargetBox="[150,1435,204,1928]" captionTargetId="figure-11@5.[150,1435,189,1928]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 3. Head (A–F), pronotum (G–K) and external scent efferent system (L) of Exosehirus species.A, G, L – E. validus (Jakovlev, 1877); B, H – E. sargon Linnavuori, 1984; C, I – E. elamensis sp. nov.; D, E, J – E. essedonius sp. nov.; F, K – E. marginatus (Signoret, 1881). Scale bars: 0.25 mm (A, C–F, L) and 0.5 mm (G, I–K). B and H after Lංඇඇൺඏඎඈ*©ං (1984)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037290" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037290/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Pronotum with anterolateral margins more widely diverging posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[473,546,1148,1171]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[150,181,2008,2027]" captionTargetBox="[150,1435,204,1928]" captionTargetId="figure-11@5.[150,1435,189,1928]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 3. Head (A–F), pronotum (G–K) and external scent efferent system (L) of Exosehirus species.A, G, L – E. validus (Jakovlev, 1877); B, H – E. sargon Linnavuori, 1984; C, I – E. elamensis sp. nov.; D, E, J – E. essedonius sp. nov.; F, K – E. marginatus (Signoret, 1881). Scale bars: 0.25 mm (A, C–F, L) and 0.5 mm (G, I–K). B and H after Lංඇඇൺඏඎඈ*©ං (1984)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037290" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037290/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Fig. 3I</figureCitation>
) than in 
<taxonomicName box="[645,753,1148,1171]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis box="[645,753,1148,1171]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Gapon, 2021" authorityName="Gapon" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,299,1180,1203]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="essedonius" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,299,1180,1203]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. essedonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[307,395,1180,1203]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Signoret" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[407,560,1180,1203]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginatus">
<emphasis box="[407,560,1180,1203]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. marginatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and slightly more widely diverging than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1984" box="[434,540,1212,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sargon">
<emphasis box="[434,540,1212,1235]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. sargon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Punctation usually slightly larger and deeper than usual in 
<taxonomicName box="[577,685,1244,1267]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis box="[577,685,1244,1267]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Other characters of habitus as in 
<taxonomicName box="[435,541,1276,1299]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis box="[435,541,1276,1299]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,760,764,2067]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[181,298,1308,1331]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Pygophore</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[311,391,1308,1331]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[151,182,1951,1970]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,194,1836]" captionTargetId="figure-11@7.[150,1435,189,1852]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 4. Pygophore, paramere and aedeagus of Exosehirus species.A, F, G, H – E. validus (Jakovlev, 1877); B, K – E. sargon Linnavuori, 1984; C – E. elamensis sp. nov.; D, I – E. essedonius sp. nov.; E, J – E. marginatus (Signoret, 1881). Pygophore in ventrocaudal (A–E) and dorsal (F) view; paramere in lateral (G) and dorsal (H–J) view; aedeagus in lateral view (K). Abbreviations: d.inf – dorsal infolding of pygophore; l.inf – lateral infolding of pygophore; l.r – lateral ridge of subgenital plate; p.r – posterior ridge of subgenital plate; v.inf – ventral infolding of pygophore. Scale bars: 0.25 mm (A, C, D, E, F) and 0.14 mm (G–J). B and K after Lංඇඇൺඏඎඈ*©ං (1984)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037292/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
) and 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[446,550,1308,1331]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">paramere</emphasis>
mostly as in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Median notch of posteroventral margin of pygophore less wide and deep than in 
<taxonomicName box="[445,552,1372,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis box="[445,552,1372,1395]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and less wide than in 
<taxonomicName authority="Gapon, 2021" authorityName="Gapon" authorityYear="2021" box="[179,325,1404,1427]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="essedonius" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[179,325,1404,1427]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. essedonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[332,415,1404,1427]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Dorsal wall of paramere corpus before base of hypophysis without distinct tubercle as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Gapon, 2021" authorityName="Gapon" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,297,1468,1491]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="essedonius" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,297,1468,1491]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. essedonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[303,386,1468,1491]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<figureCitation box="[400,475,1468,1491]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[151,182,1951,1970]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,194,1836]" captionTargetId="figure-11@7.[150,1435,189,1852]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 4. Pygophore, paramere and aedeagus of Exosehirus species.A, F, G, H – E. validus (Jakovlev, 1877); B, K – E. sargon Linnavuori, 1984; C – E. elamensis sp. nov.; D, I – E. essedonius sp. nov.; E, J – E. marginatus (Signoret, 1881). Pygophore in ventrocaudal (A–E) and dorsal (F) view; paramere in lateral (G) and dorsal (H–J) view; aedeagus in lateral view (K). Abbreviations: d.inf – dorsal infolding of pygophore; l.inf – lateral infolding of pygophore; l.r – lateral ridge of subgenital plate; p.r – posterior ridge of subgenital plate; v.inf – ventral infolding of pygophore. Scale bars: 0.25 mm (A, C, D, E, F) and 0.14 mm (G–J). B and K after Lංඇඇൺඏඎඈ*©ං (1984)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037292/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Fig. 4I</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,760,764,2067]" lastBlockId="18.[828,1437,190,1653]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[181,288,1500,1523]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Aedeagus</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[300,410,1500,1523]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[151,183,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,208,1514]" captionTargetId="figure-270@9.[151,1436,189,1518]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 6. Wet preparations of conjunctival lobes of Exosehirus species. A–C – E. validus (Jakovlev, 1877); D–F – E. sargon Linnavuori, 1984; G–I – E. elamensis sp. nov.; J–L – E. essedonius sp. nov. Ventrolateral lobe (A, D, G, J); dorsolateral lobe (B, E, H, K); dorsoapical lobe (C, F, I, L). Scale bar: 0.14 mm. D–F after Lංඇඇൺඏඎඈ*©ං (1984)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037296/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Figs 6G–I</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[419,434,1500,1523]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[151,182,876,895]" captionTargetBox="[157,1420,223,850]" captionTargetId="figure-13@10.[151,1436,189,855]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 7. Vesica of Exosehirus elamensis sp. nov., lateral view.Abbreviations: a.s – articular sclerites; d.ej.r – distal part of ejaculatory reservoir; dc.ej – ductus ejaculatorius; i.f.c – internal fold of wall of conjunctiva; p.ej.r – proximal part of ejaculatory reservoir. Border between conjunctiva and vesica shown by arrows. Scale bar: 0.14 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037298" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037298/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[444,458,1500,1523]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[960,992,1996,2015]" captionTargetBox="[169,1437,202,2069]" captionTargetId="figure-11@13.[150,1435,189,2079]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 9. Completely inflated aedeagus of Exosehirus elamensis sp. nov. A – ventral view; B – lateral view; C – dorsal view. Scale bar: 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037304" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037304/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">9</figureCitation>
) similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[648,753,1500,1523]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis box="[648,753,1500,1523]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Conjunctiva longer, about as long as theca and phallobase combined. Ventrolateral lobes slightly narrower, with slightly narrower apices bordered by wider band; bands on mesal margins of lobes more convergent; bands on anterior margins of lobes shorter. Dorsolateral lobes slightly longer, becoming wider apically in lateral view, directed anteriad (towards base of conjunctiva); ventral wall of each lobe before apex with short, narrow transverse sclerite, its lateral rounded margin protruding beyond lateral wall of lobe; any denticles on sclerites absent [
<emphasis box="[574,596,1820,1843]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">vs</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1984" box="[610,714,1820,1843]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sargon">
<emphasis box="[610,714,1820,1843]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. sargon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Gapon, 2021" authorityName="Gapon" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,295,1852,1875]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="essedonius" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,295,1852,1875]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. essedonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[300,386,1852,1875]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
]. Dorsoapical lobes almost completely transformed into spicules, being long, straight, directed dorsally and slightly anteriad, slightly diverging. In anterior view, each spicule wide at base, gradually tapering distally, with grooved concave surface; apically, spicule very narrow, without depression; in lateral view, spicule narrow throughout, thinning apicad, slightly curved; membranous wall preserved only at extreme base of spicule at anterior side; apex of spicule acute. Vesica (
<figureCitation box="[1210,1275,222,245]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[151,182,876,895]" captionTargetBox="[157,1420,223,850]" captionTargetId="figure-13@10.[151,1436,189,855]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 7. Vesica of Exosehirus elamensis sp. nov., lateral view.Abbreviations: a.s – articular sclerites; d.ej.r – distal part of ejaculatory reservoir; dc.ej – ductus ejaculatorius; i.f.c – internal fold of wall of conjunctiva; p.ej.r – proximal part of ejaculatory reservoir. Border between conjunctiva and vesica shown by arrows. Scale bar: 0.14 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037298" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037298/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) very long, directed ventrally and anteriorly, parallel to ventral wall of conjunctiva and reaching its base. Membranous tubercle at base of ventral wall trapezoidally rounded, adjacent to conjunctival wall. Walls of proximal part of conjunctiva slightly sclerotised in middle, membranous and slightly swollen just before apex. Distal part of vesica extended into relatively long filament.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[828,1437,190,1653]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[858,1060,478,501]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Female terminalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1074,1150,478,501]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[150,181,1524,1543]" captionTargetBox="[170,1373,194,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-11@21.[150,1435,157,1507]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 14. Female terminalia of Exosehirus elamensis sp. nov.A – terminalia in dorsal view (female with folded gynatrial cone); B – straight gynatrial cone of another female, in dorsoposterior view. Scale bar: 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037316" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037316/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) similar to those of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Extreme lateral ends of gonocoxites II curved inward.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[828,1437,190,1653]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">
Anterior part of gynatrial sac slightly smaller; its lateral walls almost parallel, dorsal wall slightly concave anterior to transverse fold [perhaps this shape is a consequence that the gynatrial sac in the studied females did not fully expand and swelled under the action of osmotic forces when boiling in alkali]. Gynatrial cone about three times as long as in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; its posterior part shorter and wider, without pouches on sides, anterior part much longer, more flattened, with a straight [not ventricose 
<emphasis box="[1071,1093,798,821]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">vs</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Gapon, 2021" authorityName="Gapon" authorityYear="2021" box="[1104,1245,798,821]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="essedonius" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1104,1245,798,821]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. essedonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1250,1333,798,821]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
] posterior wall, with parallel lateral margins in middle, tapering triangularly apically [in one of the two studied females, gynatrial cone is straight (
<figureCitation box="[1000,1096,894,917]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[150,181,1524,1543]" captionTargetBox="[170,1373,194,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-11@21.[150,1435,157,1507]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 14. Female terminalia of Exosehirus elamensis sp. nov.A – terminalia in dorsal view (female with folded gynatrial cone); B – straight gynatrial cone of another female, in dorsoposterior view. Scale bar: 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037316" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037316/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Fig. 14B</figureCitation>
), in the other female, it is folded twice at the base (
<figureCitation box="[1017,1115,926,949]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[150,181,1524,1543]" captionTargetBox="[170,1373,194,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-11@21.[150,1435,157,1507]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 14. Female terminalia of Exosehirus elamensis sp. nov.A – terminalia in dorsal view (female with folded gynatrial cone); B – straight gynatrial cone of another female, in dorsoposterior view. Scale bar: 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5037316" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5037316/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Fig. 14A</figureCitation>
); I do not know which state of this structure is normal]. Spermatheca attached to gynatrial cone at its apex. Proximal part of spermathecal duct slightly wider and longer than in 
<taxonomicName box="[1090,1194,1022,1045]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis box="[1090,1194,1022,1045]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, not narrowed distally; middle part substantially wider, longer (not less than twice), with parallel walls throughout; distal part slightly longer. Margins of ring sclerites slightly wider than that in typical cases in 
<taxonomicName box="[921,1028,1150,1173]" class="Insecta" family="Cydnidae" genus="Exosehirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis box="[921,1028,1150,1173]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">E. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Posterior pouches spaced apart, with widely rounded posterior margins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="151" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="18.[828,1437,190,1653]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[858,1019,1214,1237]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Measurements</emphasis>
(n = 7; mm). Body: length 5.25–6.25, width 3.25–3.93; ratio body length / pronotum width 1.75– 1.84; head: length 1.05–1.19, width 1.33–1.46; ratio width / length 1.22–1.29; synthlipsis 0.85–0.95; ocular index 3.54–3.89; length of antennal segments I–V: 0.35–0.42: 0.43–0.49: 0.36–0.41: 0.59–0.67: 0.71–0.73; pronotum: length 1.53–1.75, width 3.00–3.45, ratio width / length 1.94–1.97; scutellum: length 2.18–2.58, width 1.95–2.33, ratio length / width 1.09–1.11.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="151" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="18.[828,1437,190,1653]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,959,1502,1525]" pageId="18" pageNumber="151">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is an adjective derived from the Sumerian name of the state that existed until the 6th century BC in the territory where the new species was found.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
